Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Understanding customer personality and behavior is pivotal for businesses to enhance customer satisfaction and increase revenue. Segmentation based on a customer's personality, demographics, and purchasing behavior allows companies to create tailored marketing campaigns, improve customer retention, and optimize product offerings.

A leading retail company with a rapidly growing customer base seeks to gain deeper insights into their customers' profiles. The company recognizes that understanding customer personalities, lifestyles, and purchasing habits can unlock significant opportunities for personalizing marketing strategies and creating loyalty programs. These insights can help address critical business challenges, such as improving the effectiveness of marketing campaigns, identifying high-value customer groups, and fostering long-term relationships with customers.

With the competition intensifying in the retail space, moving away from generic strategies to more targeted and personalized approaches is essential for sustaining a competitive edge.

Objective¶

In an effort to optimize marketing efficiency and enhance customer experience, the company has embarked on a mission to identify distinct customer segments. By understanding the characteristics, preferences, and behaviors of each group, the company aims to:

  1. Develop personalized marketing campaigns to increase conversion rates.
  2. Create effective retention strategies for high-value customers.
  3. Optimize resource allocation, such as inventory management, pricing strategies, and store layouts.

As a data scientist tasked with this project, your responsibility is to analyze the given customer data, apply machine learning techniques to segment the customer base, and provide actionable insights into the characteristics of each segment.

Data Dictionary¶

The dataset includes historical data on customer demographics, personality traits, and purchasing behaviors. Key attributes are:

  1. Customer Information

    • ID: Unique identifier for each customer.
    • Year_Birth: Customer's year of birth.
    • Education: Education level of the customer.
    • Marital_Status: Marital status of the customer.
    • Income: Yearly household income (in dollars).
    • Kidhome: Number of children in the household.
    • Teenhome: Number of teenagers in the household.
    • Dt_Customer: Date when the customer enrolled with the company.
    • Recency: Number of days since the customer’s last purchase.
    • Complain: Whether the customer complained in the last 2 years (1 for yes, 0 for no).

  2. Spending Information (Last 2 Years)

    • MntWines: Amount spent on wine.
    • MntFruits: Amount spent on fruits.
    • MntMeatProducts: Amount spent on meat.
    • MntFishProducts: Amount spent on fish.
    • MntSweetProducts: Amount spent on sweets.
    • MntGoldProds: Amount spent on gold products.

  3. Purchase and Campaign Interaction

    • NumDealsPurchases: Number of purchases made using a discount.
    • AcceptedCmp1: Response to the 1st campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp2: Response to the 2nd campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp3: Response to the 3rd campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp4: Response to the 4th campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp5: Response to the 5th campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • Response: Response to the last campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).

  4. Shopping Behavior

    • NumWebPurchases: Number of purchases made through the company’s website.
    • NumCatalogPurchases: Number of purchases made using catalogs.
    • NumStorePurchases: Number of purchases made directly in stores.
    • NumWebVisitsMonth: Number of visits to the company’s website in the last month.

Question 3: Are there any missing values in the data? If yes, treat them using an appropriate method¶

In [32]:
# Check for missing values in the dataset
missing_values = df.isnull().sum()

# Display missing values for each column
missing_summary = missing_values[missing_values > 0]
print("Missing Values Summary:\n", missing_summary)

# For numerical columns, fill missing values with the median
numerical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns
df[numerical_columns] = df[numerical_columns].fillna(df[numerical_columns].median())

# For categorical columns, fill missing values with the mode
categorical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=[object]).columns
for col in categorical_columns:
    df[col] = df[col].fillna(df[col].mode()[0])

# Verify that there are no missing values left
missing_values_after = df.isnull().sum()
print("Missing Values After Treatment:\n", missing_values_after[missing_values_after > 0])

K-means Clustering¶

Question 7 : Select the appropriate number of clusters using the elbow Plot. What do you think is the appropriate number of clusters?¶

In [36]:
# Determine the optimal number of clusters using the elbow method
inertia = []
k_values = range(1, 11)

# for simplicity, only consider numerical data
numerical_data = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).drop(columns=['ID'])

for k in k_values:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(numerical_data)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot the elbow curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(k_values, inertia, marker='o')
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal k")
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (k)")
plt.ylabel("Inertia")
plt.xticks(k_values)
plt.grid()
plt.show()
Observations:¶
  1. The intertia starts to descrease slowly at K = 4.
  2. This suggests that using 4 clusters captures the variations in the data effectively without overfitting.

silhouette_scores = []

for k in range(2, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(numerical_data)
    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score(numerical_data, kmeans_labels))

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Question 10: Calculate the cophnetic correlation for every combination of distance metrics and linkage. Which combination has the highest cophnetic correlation?¶

In [39]:
# Define distance metrics and linkage methods
distance_metrics = ['euclidean', 'cityblock', 'cosine']
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'ward']

# Initialize results list
results = []

# Calculate cophenetic correlation for specified combinations
for metric in distance_metrics:
    for method in linkage_methods:
        # Skip incompatible combinations
        if method == 'ward' and metric != 'euclidean':
            continue
            
        # Calculate the linkage matrix
        Z = linkage(numerical_data, method=method, metric=metric)
        
        # Calculate the cophenetic distance
        coph_dist, _ = cophenet(Z, pdist(numerical_data, metric=metric))
        
        # Store results
        results.append((metric, method, coph_dist))

# Convert results to DataFrame for easier analysis
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results, columns=['Distance Metric', 'Linkage Method', 'Cophenetic Correlation'])

# Find the combination with the highest cophenetic correlation
highest_coph_corr = results_df.loc[results_df['Cophenetic Correlation'].idxmax()]

print("Combination with the highest cophenetic correlation:")
print(highest_coph_corr)

Combination with the highest cophenetic correlation:
Distance Metric             cosine
Linkage Method             average
Cophenetic Correlation    0.957899
Name: 9, dtype: object
Observations:¶
  1. The cosine distance metric measures the cosine of the angle between two non-zero vectors. It is particularly useful for high-dimensional data where the magnitude of the vectors may not be as important as their direction. This suggests that your data may have a high dimensionality or that the relationships between the points are more about their orientation rather than their absolute distances.
  2. The average linkage method calculates the distance between clusters as the average distance between all pairs of points in the two clusters. This method is less sensitive to outliers compared to other linkage methods (like single or complete linkage). It indicates a more balanced approach to cluster formation.
  3. A cophenetic correlation of approximately 0.88 is quite high, suggesting that the clustering structure represented by the dendrogram is a good reflection of the actual pairwise distances in the dataset. This means that the clustering method used effectively captures the relationships among the data points.

Z_single = linkage(numerical_data, method='single')
Z_complete = linkage(numerical_data, method='complete')
Z_average = linkage(numerical_data, method='average')
Z_ward = linkage(numerical_data, method='ward')

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

# Create dendrograms
dendrogram(Z_single, ax=axes[0, 0], color_threshold=0)
axes[0, 0].set_title('Dendrogram using Single Linkage', fontsize=14)
axes[0, 0].set_xlabel('Samples', fontsize=12)
axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Distance', fontsize=12)
axes[0, 0].grid(axis='y')

dendrogram(Z_complete, ax=axes[0, 1], color_threshold=0)
axes[0, 1].set_title('Dendrogram using Complete Linkage', fontsize=14)
axes[0, 1].set_xlabel('Samples', fontsize=12)
axes[0, 1].set_ylabel('Distance', fontsize=12)
axes[0, 1].grid(axis='y')

dendrogram(Z_average, ax=axes[1, 0], color_threshold=0)
axes[1, 0].set_title('Dendrogram using Average Linkage', fontsize=14)
axes[1, 0].set_xlabel('Samples', fontsize=12)
axes[1, 0].set_ylabel('Distance', fontsize=12)
axes[1, 0].grid(axis='y')

dendrogram(Z_ward, ax=axes[1, 1], color_threshold=0)
axes[1, 1].set_title('Dendrogram using Ward Linkage', fontsize=14)
axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Samples', fontsize=12)
axes[1, 1].set_ylabel('Distance', fontsize=12)
axes[1, 1].grid(axis='y')

# Adjust line thickness after creating the dendrogram
for ax in axes.flat:
    for line in ax.get_lines():
        line.set_linewidth(1.5)  # Set a new line width

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Observations:¶
  1. Single Linkage: Tends to produce long, thin clusters. Look for "chaining" effects where clusters may merge based on a few close points.
  2. Complete Linkage: Typically results in more compact clusters. It may create a more balanced dendrogram, where clusters are more evenly sized.
  3. Average Linkage: Balances the characteristics of both single and complete linkage. It may give a good representation of the data structure.
  4. Ward's Method: Aims to minimize the variance within clusters. It often results in well-separated clusters and is generally effective for most datasets.

# Calculate silhouette scores for each number of clusters
silhouette_avg_list = []

for n_clusters in range_n_clusters:
    # Start the timer
    start_time = time.time()

    # Perform hierarchical clustering
    clusterer = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=n_clusters, metric='euclidean', linkage='ward')
    cluster_labels = clusterer.fit_predict(numerical_data)

    # Stop the timer
    end_time = time.time()

    # Calculate the time taken
    time_taken = end_time - start_time
    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(numerical_data, cluster_labels)

    print(f'For n_clusters = {n_clusters}, the average silhouette score is: {silhouette_avg:.4f}')
    print(f'Time taken to fit the model: {time_taken:.4f} seconds\n')

  2. Time Taken: The time taken to fit the model generally decreases as the number of clusters increases, likely due to fewer computations needed as the model complexity decreases with higher cluster numbers. The fitting time is relatively quick, ranging from about 0.206 to 0.478 seconds.

cluster_count = 3
sns.set(style="whitegrid", palette="pastel")

# Scale the numerical features
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_data = scaler.fit_transform(numerical_data.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]))

# K-Means Clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=cluster_count, random_state=42)
numerical_data['KMeans_Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(scaled_data)

# Hierarchical Clustering
linkage_matrix = linkage(scaled_data, method='ward')
numerical_data['Hierarchical_Cluster'] = fcluster(linkage_matrix, t=cluster_count, criterion='maxclust')

# Create a figure with two subplots side by side
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 8))

# Boxplot for K-Means Clusters
sns.boxplot(x='KMeans_Cluster', y='Income', data=numerical_data, showmeans=True, width=0.5, ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title('K-Means Clustering Profile', fontsize=18)
axes[0].set_xlabel('K-Means Cluster', fontsize=14)
axes[0].set_ylabel('Income (Log Scale)', fontsize=14)
axes[0].set_yscale('log')  # Set y-axis to logarithmic scale
axes[0].grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
axes[0].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# Boxplot for Hierarchical Clusters
sns.boxplot(x='Hierarchical_Cluster', y='Income', data=numerical_data, showmeans=True, width=0.5, ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title('Hierarchical Clustering Profile', fontsize=18)
axes[1].set_xlabel('Hierarchical Cluster', fontsize=14)
axes[1].set_ylabel('Income (Log Scale)', fontsize=14)
axes[1].set_yscale('log')  # Set y-axis to logarithmic scale
axes[1].grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
axes[1].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)

# Adjust layout to prevent overlap
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Observations:¶

K-Means Cluster:

  • Each cluster has distinct median income values, indicating clear segmentation. The median values vary significantly across different clusters.
  • The IQRs varies among clusters.
  • There are noticeable outliers in some clusters, which may indicate that K-Means is less effective in capturing the underlying structure of the data for those segments.

Hiearchical Cluster:

  • Similar to K-Means, the median incomes are different across the clusters.
  • The IQRs also varies among clusters.
  • Outliers looks more than K-Means.

Conclusion: Since K-Means Cluster has fewer outliers, it can conclude that it captures the data structure more effectively. Therefore, K-Means provides better clustering in this case.

# Identify features to remove
features_to_remove = [col for col in numerical_data.columns if '_Label' in col or col.startswith('Z_') or col == 'Hierarchical_Cluster']
filtered_numerical_data = numerical_data.drop(columns=features_to_remove)

# Calculate the means for each cluster
cluster_means = filtered_numerical_data.groupby('KMeans_Cluster').mean().reset_index()

# Melt the DataFrame for easier plotting
cluster_means_melted = cluster_means.melt(id_vars='KMeans_Cluster', 
                                            var_name='Feature', 
                                            value_name='Mean')

# Apply log transformation for better visualization
cluster_means_melted['Mean'] = np.log1p(cluster_means_melted['Mean'])  # log(1 + x)

# Create the barplot
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.barplot(x='Feature', y='Mean', hue='KMeans_Cluster', data=cluster_means_melted)

plt.ylabel('Log of Mean Value', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Feature', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title='Cluster')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Observations:¶
  1. The order of income levels are: Cluster 1 (High), Cluster 2 (Medium), Cluster 0 (Low).
  2. The 3 clusters have similar pattern across key features such as wines, fruits, meat and sweet products. The order is cluster 1, 2 and 0. This is reasonable as higher incomes imply more purchases.
  3. All 3 clusters have significant amount of purchases in deals, web, catalog and store. Cluster of lowests incomes have smallest web purchases and highest store purchases.
  4. Clusters of medium and high incomes have significant deals purchases and catalog purchases.
  5. All 3 clusters have very low response rate to marketing compaign.
  6. All 3 clusters have low to zero complaint rate.
  7. All 3 cluster have low rate of web visits.
  8. Low-income cluster tends to have more kid or teen(s).
Business Recommedations:¶
  1. Strengthen the sales of key products by offering more diversified product brands, cross-selling discounts across different key products.
  2. Offer more high priced wines and meats to attract medium and high-income clusters.
  3. Offer more ad-hoc or seasonal discount sales for key products to boost up web purchases.
  4. Offer some products with special discounts/limit-time offers for web purchases. This may encourage more web purchases from low-income customers.
  5. Strengthen catalog sales by providing convenient channels, product catalog, etc.
  6. Review and improve web site or app in order to attract more web visits.
  7. Launch more marketing events to attract more customer response rate, or evalualte the accessibility of response channels.
  8. While the complaint rate is low, it may be better to provide channels of customer feedback. Display customer feedbacks in retail stores. This may improve customer experiences and loyalty.
  9. While gold products are high worth products, strengthen the sales by offering more product types and discounts.
  10. Offer some products trageting kids or teens.
